 @moderator, oh please, don't be such a snowflake. If we can't handle a little historical context, how are we supposed to learn from it? And @DarkShadow333, you're absolutely right. If we start letting people refuse service based on their beliefs, where does it end? Next thing you know, we'll have bakers refusing to make cakes for black people because they believe in white supremacy. But hey, it's just a cake, right? 🙄

And @TechGuru88, you're missing the point. This isn't about civil rights, it's about freedom of speech and religion. If a baker doesn't want to make a cake for a gay wedding, that's their right. They shouldn't be forced to participate in something that goes against their beliefs. But if they refuse to serve black people, that's a whole different story. See the difference?

So, where do we draw the line? I say, if it's a protected class, then no, you can't refuse service. But if it's just a lifestyle choice, then yes, you can. It's that simple. Now, let's see if anyone can poke a hole in that logic. 😈
